### Other

_No response_

### What would you like?

Today, when we use the `cy.request()` command, e.g.:

```typescript
cy.request({
  url: tokenUrl,
  method: 'POST',
  body: {
    grant_type: 'password',
    client_secret: clientSecret,
    username,
    password,
    ...,
  },
});
```

if the request fails, the Cypress error reporter will log the *entire* request.  
In other words, it would potentially leak the secrets contained in the request body in the logs.

The feature request: **have a way to mask/suppress part of the logged request** 🙏

### Why is this needed?

As you may have noted, this is very problematic from a security point of view.  
Indeed, suppose the job is run on a CI environment, then a lot of people could have access to the logs and so to the secrets.  
Admittedly, it often concerns a development environment, maybe a pre-production one; but still, this is not security compliant.

### Other

The current "workaround":

```typescript
const requestOptions = { ...payload, failOnStatusCode: false, log: false };
return cy.request(requestOptions).then((response) => {
  if (response.status === 200) {
    return response;
  } else {
    throw new Error(`Request ended with status ${response.status}`);
  }
});
```

but I do not think that it works for any kind of error (e.g.: https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/issues/28175)

Please see also:

* Previous discussion: https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/discussions/19109#discussioncomment-7365544 (Nov 2021)
* Previous issue: https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/issues/20214 (Feb 2022)

