### Current behavior

Assuming I have customized the **React** `cy.mount` command to load **Styled Components** global styles via the `GlobalStyle` component, I expect the following to happen:

- The component mounted by `cy.mount` is loaded with the styles from **Styled Components** :white_check_mark:
- The component re rendered by `rerender` is loaded with the styles from **Styled Components** :x: 

#### Component style by `mount`

![image](https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/assets/85199880/100bbaea-6652-489b-bdfa-c4666d74fb4e)

#### Same component style by `rerender`

![image](https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/assets/85199880/50dc383e-6046-4201-987e-53e91e59c9cb)


### Desired behavior

Replicate customization from `cy.mount` to `rerender`, so the **Styled Components** styles are loading during the rerender and the component is rendered with the same UI as when it was mounted.

#### Component style by `mount`

![image](https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/assets/85199880/100bbaea-6652-489b-bdfa-c4666d74fb4e)

#### Same component style by `rerender`

![image](https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/assets/85199880/100bbaea-6652-489b-bdfa-c4666d74fb4e)


### Test code to reproduce

```tsx
// support/component.tsx

import { styled, createGlobalStyle } from 'styled-components';

const GlobalStyle = createGlobalStyle`
  :root {
    --primary-color: red;
  }
`

Cypress.Commands.add('mount', (component, options = {}) => {
  const wrapped = (
      <Fragment>
          <GlobalStyle />
          {component}
      </Fragment>
  );
  
  return mount(wrapped, options);
})

const Button = styled.button`
  background-color: var(--primary-color);
`;

cy.mount(<Button  />).then(({ rerender }) => {
    // Button background is red!
    cy.get('button').click();

    rerender(<Button />).then(() => {
        // Button background is not red :cry: 
        cy.get('button').should('have.css', 'background-color');
    });
});

```

### Cypress Version

12.12

### Node version

16.20.1

### Operating System

Linux Mint 20.2 Cinnamon

### Debug Logs

_No response_

### Other

The example code has been simplified to make it easier to understand.

### What would you like?

I would like to be able to provide auth credentials as part of the initial Cypress install. We use a corporate Nexus which is authenticated (ours with basic auth). The docs and help generally say "download file first, then use `CYPRESS_INSTALL_BINARY` to the local file".

@cypress/request already allows for basic auth, but on `./node_modules/cypress/index.js --exec install` the call to request in cypress/lib/tasks/download.js doesn't provide a mechanism for providing `auth`. I modified my local Cypress installation (cypress/lib/tasks/download.js), and was able to install with:

```sh
CYPRESS_INSTALL_BINARY=http://corporate-nexus/path/to/cypress.zip user=USERNAME pass=PASSWORD node ./node_modules/cypress/index.js --exec install
```

The modification in short was:

```js
// cypress/lib/tasks/download.js
const getAuth = (ca) => {
  return new Promise(resolve => {
    if (process.env.user && process.env.pass) {
      resolve({ ca, auth: { user: process.env.user, pass: process.env.pass })
    } else {
      resolve({ ca })
    }
  }
}

const downloadFromUrl = ({
  url,
  downloadDestination,
  progress,
  ca,
  auth,
  //...
  const reqOptions = {
    //...
    ..(auth ? { auth } : {}),

const start = saync opts => {
//...
}).then(ca) => {
   return getAuth(ca);
}).then({ca, auth}) => {
  url: versionUrl,
  downloadDestination,
  progress,
  ca,
  auth,
  //...
```

### Why is this needed?

We have to mirror in a non-standard location the Cypress binaries within our corporate network on Nexus. Our corporate Nexus has authentication on it. To simplify developer experience and pipeline integration, it would be good on install if authentication could be passed to the request to download the binary.

